Amanda Khoza, News24Durban - The Durban High Court is expected to rule on the Shembe Church leadership debacle on Tuesday. &nbsp;Vela Shembe and his nephew, Mduduzi Shembe, who is the son of the late leader, Vimbeni Shembe are fighting over the control of the multi-million rand African religious church.&nbsp;Shembe's, Vela Shembe, arrives at the Durban High Court where he is challenging the right to lead the multi-million member church. @News24 pic.twitter.com/5H2M10v6AlShembe's Mduduzi Shembe arrives at the Durban Hugh Court for the historic announcement into the the leadership debacle. @News24 pic.twitter.com/dQgusX1M17&mdash; Amanda Khoza (@MandaKhoza) October 18, 2016Shembe's Mduduzi Shembe arrives at the Durban Hugh Court for the historic announcement into the the leadership debacle. @News24 pic.twitter.com/dQgusX1M17 The tug of war erupted in 2011 on the day of Vimbeni's funeral when his childhood friend, Inkosi Mqoqi Ngcobo, announced that Mduduzi was the rightful heir to the throne and the speaker who followed him, Zwelibanzi Buthelezi, who had been Vimbeni's lawyer, read the deed of nomination in which he announced that Vela was the successor.Loud cheers as Shembe's Mduduzi Shembe arrives at the Durban High Court. pic.twitter.com/R54cqedNsiThere was a high police presence outside the courtroom on Tuesday comprising of Metro Police, SAPS Public Order and a Tactical Response Unit.&nbsp;The two factions of the church violently clashed outside the court last year April.&nbsp;24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.